M|references|- **Industry:** B2B SaaS (project management software)
M|references|- **Revenue at start:** $3.2M ARR
M|references|- **Employees:** 35
M|references|- **Founded:** 4 years prior
M|references|- **Leadership team:** CEO (Visionary), COO (Integrator), VP Sales, VP Engineering, VP mkt
M|references|- Revenue growth had stalled at 15% year-over-year after three years of 80%+ growth
M|references|- The CEO was involved in every dec, creating a bottleneck
M|references|- Engineering and Sales were in constant conflict over roadmap priorities
M|references|- No formal meeting rhythm; ad hoc meetings consumed 30+ hours per week across leadership
M|references|- Three key engineers quit in six months, citing lack of direction
M|references|**Quarter 1:** Focus Day established the Accountability Chart. The CEO stepped into the Visionary role and the COO formally became the Integrator. Weekly Level 10 meetings replaced all ad hoc leadersh
M|references|**Quarter 2:** V/TO completed. Core Values defined: "Ship It," "Customer Obsessed," "Radical Candor." Core Focus: "Make teams productive" + "Project management for mid-market SaaS." A weekly Scorecard
M|references|**Quarter 3:** People Analyzer run on all 35 employees. Four people were identified as wrong person/wrong seat. Two were moved to better-fitting roles. Two exited. The engineering-sales conflict was I
M|references|**Quarter 4:** Department-level Level 10 meetings rolled out. Department scorecards created. Rock completion rate hit 85%.
M|references|| Metric | Before EOS | After 12 Months | After 24 Months |
M|references||--------|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| ARR | $3.2M | $4.8M | $7.1M |
M|references|| ARR Growth | 15% | 50% | 48% |
M|references|| Employee Headcount | 35 | 48 | 65 |
M|references|| Employee Turnover | 28% annually | 12% | 8% |
M|references|| Rock Completion | N/A | 75% | 88% |
M|references|| Level 10 Score | N/A | 7.2 avg | 8.6 avg |
M|references|| CEO Weekly Hours in Meetings | 32 | 12 | 8 |
M|references|- **Month 0-3:** Foundation (Focus Day, VB1, VB2). Immediate reduction in ad hoc meetings.
M|references|- **Month 3-6:** First quarterly ses. Scorecard revealing blind spots in customer health metrics.
M|references|- **Month 6-12:** People decisions made. Core processes documented. Revenue growth resumed.
M|references|- **Month 12-24:** EOS cascaded to all departments. Company operating as a self-managing system.
M|references|1. The CEO stepping out of day-to-day operations and into the Visionary role unlocked growth that was being bottlenecked by one person.
M|references|2. The engineering-sales conflict was not a people problem -- it was a process problem. Documenting the roadmap prioritization process resolved years of tension.
M|references|3. The weekly Scorecard caught a customer health decline that would have resulted in major churn if not addressed early.
M|references|- **Industry:** Management consulting
M|references|- **Revenue at start:** $8.5M
M|references|- **Employees:** 52
M|references|- **Founded:** 12 years prior
M|references|- **Leadership team:** Managing Partner (Visionary), COO (Integrator), 3 Practice Leads, Head of Business dev
M|references|- Revenue had plateaued for two years despite adding consultants
M|references|- Utilization rates varied wildly (50% to 95%) across practices
M|references|- No consistent delivery methodology; quality depended entirely on the individual consultant
M|references|- The Managing Partner was the only person who could close large deals
M|references|- High-potential consultants kept leaving for cp
M|references|**Focus Day:** Accountability Chart revealed that no one owned business dev as a full-time function. The Managing Partner had been doing it as a side task. A Head of Business dev seat was created.
M|references|**V/TO Sessions:** Core Values: "Client First," "Own Your Craft," "Straight Talk," "Win Together." mkt str identified the ideal client profile (mid-market companies, $50M-$500M revenue, undergoing ope
M|references|**Process Documentation:** Three core processes were documented: "The Engagement Lifecycle" (sales to delivery to follow-up), "The Consulting Method" (the firm's proprietary delivery approach), and "T
M|references|**Scorecard:** Key metrics included weekly utilization rate, pl value, proposals outstanding, consultant satisfaction score, and client NPS.
M|references|| Metric | Before EOS | After 12 Months | After 24 Months |
M|references||--------|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Revenue | $8.5M | $10.2M | $13.8M |
M|references|| Utilization Rate | 62% avg | 74% avg | 78% avg |
M|references|| Revenue Per Consultant | $212K | $268K | $310K |
M|references|| Consultant Turnover | 35% | 18% | 12% |
M|references|| Client NPS | 42 | 58 | 67 |
M|references|| Rock Completion | N/A | 70% | 82% |
M|references|| Level 10 Score | N/A | 6.8 avg | 8.3 avg |
M|references|1. Documenting the delivery methodology ("The Consulting Method") was the single highest-impact change. It made quality consistent across all consultants and reduced the firm's dependence on individua
M|references|2. Utilization rate visibility on the weekly Scorecard changed behavior immediately. Practice leads started managing capacity proactively instead of reactively.
M|references|3. Hiring a dedicated Head of Business dev freed the Managing Partner to focus on strategic relationships, which paradoxically increased deal flow.
M|references|- **Industry:** Custom metal fabrication
M|references|- **Revenue at start:** $18M
M|references|- **Employees:** 120
M|references|- **Founded:** 25 years prior (second-generation family business)
M|references|- **Leadership team:** Owner/President (Visionary), General Manager (Integrator), VP Sales, Plant Manager, Controller
M|references|- Profit margins had declined from 12% to 5% over five years
M|references|- On-time delivery rate was 71%, causing customer complaints and lost contracts
M|references|- The shop floor had no documented processes; veteran machinists each had their own methods
M|references|- The owner's son had been promoted to Plant Manager but was struggling
M|references|- No weekly management meetings; monthly financial reviews were the only rhythm
M|references|**People Component:** The People Analyzer revealed the owner's son did not have the Capacity for the Plant Manager role. After a difficult but honest conversation, he moved to a Business dev role wher
M|references|**Process Component:** Five core shop floor processes were documented with the 20/80 rule. Each process was given a branded name and posted at the relevant workstation. Training was conducted over six
M|references|**Data Component:** A weekly Scorecard was installed tracking on-time delivery %, scrap rate, labor utilization, quoting turnaround time, and weekly revenue. Numbers were displayed on a large screen o
M|references|**Traction Component:** Level 10 meetings were introduced for the leadership team and the shop floor supervisors. Quarterly rocks focused on operational improvements: reducing setup times, implementin
M|references|| Metric | Before EOS | After 12 Months | After 24 Months |
M|references||--------|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Revenue | $18M | $19.5M | $22M |
M|references|| Profit Margin | 5% | 9% | 13% |
M|references|| On-Time Delivery | 71% | 88% | 94% |
M|references|| Scrap Rate | 8% | 4.5% | 2.8% |
M|references|| Customer Complaints/Month | 12 | 5 | 2 |
M|references|| Employee Turnover | 40% | 22% | 15% |
M|references|| Rock Completion | N/A | 65% | 80% |
M|references|1. The hardest dec -- moving the owner's son out of the Plant Manager role -- was also the most impactful. Using the People Analyzer made it an objective conversation rather than a personal attack.
M|references|2. Making the Scorecard visible on the shop floor created a sense of ownership among floor workers. They started self-correcting before managers even noticed problems.
M|references|3. Manufacturing companies often resist EOS because they think it is for "office businesses." Process documentation and weekly scorecards are arguably even more impactful in prd environments.
M|references|- **Industry:** Digital mkt agency
M|references|- **Revenue at start:** $4.2M
M|references|- **Employees:** 28
M|references|- **Founded:** 6 years prior
M|references|- **Leadership team:** Founder/Creative Director (Visionary), Director of Operations (Integrator), Head of Accounts, Head of Creative, Head of Media
M|references|- Revenue was growing but profitability was near zero due to scope creep on client projects
M|references|- The founder was involved in every creative dec, limiting the team's output
M|references|- Client retention was 65% (industry average is 72%)
M|references|- No standardized project delivery process; every project was a "custom" engagement
M|references|- The team operated in constant fire-drill mode with no clear priorities
M|references|**V/TO:** Core Focus defined as "Make brands unforgettable" + "Performance-driven creative for B2B tech companies." This immediately clarified which clients to pursue and which to stop serving. Three 
M|references|**Process Component:** The core delivery process ("The Impact Cycle") was documented in 12 steps from brief to launch to performance rv. Scope creep was addressed by adding a formal change request ste
M|references|**Rocks:** First quarter rocks included: define ideal client profile and update all sales materials, doc The Impact Cycle, hire a Creative Director to replace the founder in day-to-day creative decisi
M|references|**People Component:** The founder struggled to let go of creative control. An honest Visionary/Integrator conversation established boundaries: the founder would set creative direction and handle top-t
M|references|| Metric | Before EOS | After 12 Months | After 24 Months |
M|references||--------|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Revenue | $4.2M | $5.1M | $6.8M |
M|references|| Net Profit Margin | 2% | 12% | 18% |
M|references|| Client Retention | 65% | 78% | 85% |
M|references|| Revenue Per Employee | $150K | $189K | $227K |
M|references|| Scope Creep Incidents/Quarter | 15+ | 4 | 1 |
M|references|| Rock Completion | N/A | 72% | 85% |
M|references|| Founder Hours/Week on prd | 35 | 15 | 5 |
M|references|1. Narrowing the niche felt counterintuitive ("We're turning away revenue!") but dramatically improved profitability and client results. Specialization commands higher prices and lower delivery costs.
M|references|2. Documenting the delivery process eliminated scope creep, which was the primary margin killer.
M|references|3. Agencies where the founder cannot delegate creative work will always have a revenue ceiling. The Visionary/Integrator framework gave the founder a path to step back without losing influence.
M|references|- **Industry:** Multi-location physical therapy practice
M|references|- **Revenue at start:** $12M
M|references|- **Employees:** 85 (across 6 clinics)
M|references|- **Founded:** 10 years prior
M|references|- **Leadership team:** Founder/CEO (Visionary), Practice Administrator (Integrator), Clinical Director, mkt Director, fin Director
M|references|- Six clinics operating independently with inconsistent patient experiences
M|references|- Clinical outcomes varied significantly by location
M|references|- Difficulty recruiting and retaining therapists (three open positions unfilled for 6+ months)
M|references|- No visibility into clinic-level performance; only aggregate monthly financials
M|references|- The founder spent all day traveling between clinics putting out fires
M|references|**Data Component:** A clinic-level weekly Scorecard was the first tool implemented. Each clinic tracked: new patient visits, patient visit volume, plan-of-care completion rate, patient satisfaction sc
M|references|**Process Component:** The clinical delivery process ("The Recovery Path") was standardized across all six locations. Best practices from the top-performing clinic were documented and rolled out to al
M|references|**People Component:** Clinic managers were assessed using GWC. Two of six managers did not have the Capacity for the expanded management role. One was moved to a senior therapist role (a better fit). 
M|references|**Traction Component:** Each clinic ran its own weekly Level 10 meeting. The leadership team's Level 10 rv company-wide Scorecard data and clinic-level issues escalated from clinic meetings.
M|references|| Metric | Before EOS | After 12 Months | After 24 Months |
M|references||--------|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Revenue | $12M | $14.5M | $18M |
M|references|| Clinics | 6 | 6 | 8 |
M|references|| Patient Satisfaction | 4.1/5 avg | 4.5/5 avg | 4.7/5 avg |
M|references|| Plan Completion Rate | 62% | 78% | 85% |
M|references|| Therapist Turnover | 30% | 15% | 10% |
M|references|| Open Therapist Positions | 3 (6+ months) | 1 (filled in 45 days) | 0 |
M|references|| Rock Completion | N/A | 68% | 83% |
M|references|| Founder Hours in Clinics/Week | 40 | 15 | 5 |
M|references|1. Multi-location businesses benefit enormously from EOS because it creates consistency across locations while maintaining local autonomy through department-level Level 10 meetings.
M|references|2. The clinic-level Scorecard was transformative. Problems that had been invisible in aggregate monthly financials became obvious in weekly clinic-level data.
M|references|3. Standardizing the clinical process actually improved therapist satisfaction because it reduced dec fatigue and gave new hires a clear playbook.
M|references|Across all case studies, consistent patterns emerge:
M|references|1. **Full leadership team commitment.** No partial adoption. Every leader attends every ses and runs Level 10 meetings in their departments.
M|references|2. **Willingness to make hard people decisions.** Every company had at least one difficult personnel change in the first year. Delaying these decisions delayed results.
M|references|3. **Process documentation early.** Companies that documented core processes in the first two quarters saw faster improvements than those who waited.
M|references|4. **Weekly Scorecard discipline.** The Scorecard catches problems early. Companies that maintained weekly discipline consistently outperformed those that slipped to biweekly or monthly reviews.
M|references|5. **The Visionary steps back.** In every case, the founder/Visionary needed to delegate operational decisions to the Integrator. This was always uncomfortable and always transformative.
M|references|| Success Factor | Successful Companies | Failed Implementations |
M|references||---------------|---------------------|----------------------|
M|references|| Commitment duration | 2+ year commitment | Quit after 6 months |
M|references|| Level 10 consistency | Never miss a meeting | Cancel when "busy" |
M|references|| People decisions | Made within 90 days | Avoided for quarters or years |
M|references|| Rocks discipline | Set SMART rocks, track weekly | Vague rocks, tracked monthly |
M|references|| Leadership alignment | Openly debate, then commit | Agree in the room, undermine outside |
M|references|| Patience with results | Expect Year 1 = foundation, Year 2 = results | Expect immediate transformation |
